<DOC><DOCNO> AP880902-0176 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 2058EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-BRF--SwineVaccine     09-02 0159</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Swine Vaccine,150</SECOND><HEAD>Test of New Swine Vaccine Slated</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Kansas City, Mo., firm has been approved toconduct a field test this fall of a genetically altered vaccinedesigned to protect swine against pseudorabies, a contagiousdisease that can be deadly to newborn pigs, the AgricultureDepartment said Friday.   The vaccine will be tested by Fermenta Animal Health Co., afterOct. 1 on hog farms in Illinois, Iowa, Indiana, Minnesota andNebraska.   James W. Glosser, administrator of the department's Animal andPlant Health Inspection Service, said three previous pseudorabiesvaccines have been field tested and licensed for manufacture.   As with the earlier tests, the Fermenta vaccine and testingprogram has been reviewed and ``will pose no significant risks tothe environment,'' he said.   Pseudorabies, also known as Aujesky's disease or mad itch, doesnot affect humans, Glosser said.   The National Pork Producers Council estimates that the diseasecaused $36 million in losses last year.</TEXT></DOC>